<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="33">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Epirhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epirhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Epirhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognised in the Afrotropical region as the species lack the fore wing areolet (vein 3rs-m is missing), whereas the areolet is closed by vein 3rs-m in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Megarhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megarhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Megarhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ashmead, the only other rhyssine genus found in the Afrotropical region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="33">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Epirhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epirhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Epirhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other rhyssine genera by the lack of an areolet (cf. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Rhyssella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhyssella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Rhyssella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rohwer, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Lytarmes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lytarmes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Lytarmes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Cameron), the lack of an anterior glymma on tergite 1 (cf. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Rhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Rhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Gravenhorst), the upper tooth being slightly wider than the lower and not subdivided (cf. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Triancyra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Triancyra" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Triancyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baltazar, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Myllenyxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myllenyxis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Myllenyxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baltazar) and the pterostigma being angled where it meets the metacarpus (compared to gradually merging in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Cyrtorhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cyrtorhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Cyrtorhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baltazar) (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="33" refId="B1">Baltazar 1964</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02027741" author="Townes, H" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" pagination="1 - 300" refId="B19" refString="Townes, H, 1969. The genera of Ichneumonidae, Part 1. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 11: 1 - 300" title="The genera of Ichneumonidae, Part 1." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02027741" volume="11" year="1969">Townes 1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, CC" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" pagination="129 - 137" refId="B13" refString="Porter, CC, 2001. New species and records of Rhyssa and Rhyssella (Hymenoptera: Ichneumonidae: Rhyssinae) from Florida and Central America. Insecta Mundi 15: 129 - 137" title="New species and records of Rhyssa and Rhyssella (Hymenoptera: Ichneumonidae: Rhyssinae) from Florida and Central America." volume="15" year="2001">Porter 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Old World 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Epirhyssa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epirhyssa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Epirhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have fore wing vein 2rs-m only a little proximal to 2m-cu, unlike New World species. The species are rather heterogeneous, with confusion with other genera particularly likely in the Oriental region, and the genus may well prove not to be monophyletic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="33" type="distribution">
